ve and often militant collection that explores a diverse range of themes including: the revisiting of the term 'queer'; a rethinking of the sex-gender distinction as being implied in Queer Theory; an exploration of queer temporalities; the non/re-reading of the homosexual body/desire and the becoming-queer of the Deleuze/Guattari philosophy. It will be essential reading for anyone interested not just in Deleuze's and Guattari's philosophy, but also in the fields of sexuality, gender and feminist theory."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHomosexualityxPhilosophy. 0aQueer theory. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aAndermatt Conley, Verena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColebrook, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHickey-Moody, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKemp, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacCormack, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNigianni, Chrysanthi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlkowski, Dorothea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParisi, Luciana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRasmussen, Mary Lou, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShildrick, Margrit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStorr, Merl, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aTuhkanen, Mikko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074863404040uhttps://doi.org/1